The causes of anxiety disorders are complicated. Many might
occur at once, some may lead to others, and some might not
lead to an anxiety disorder unless another is present.
• Environmental stressors, such as difficulties at work,
• Genetics, as people who have family members with an
anxiety disorder are more likely to experience one
• Medical factors, such as the symptoms of a different disease,
the effects of a medication, or the stress of an intensive
• Brain chemistry, as psychologists define many anxiety
disorders as misalignments of hormones and electrical signals
• Withdrawal from an illicit substance, the effects of which
might intensify the impact of other possible causes

Some anxiety is normal, but seek help if:
• You feel like you're worrying too much, and it's interfering
with your work, relationships or other parts of your life
• You feel depressed or irritable, have trouble with drinking
or drugs, or you have other mental health concerns along
• You have suicidal thoughts or behaviors —
Your worries are unlikely to simply go away on their own,
and they may actually get worse over time. Try to seek
professional help before your anxiety becomes severe — it
may be easier to treat early on.
